  <h2 id="when-to-use">When to use a card</h2>
  <p>Use a card to help users identify related content or actions they may need.</p>
  <p>You can display a card alongside other cards, but if you are grouping cards to create a hub page (sometimes called a landing page) use the <a href="https://service-manual.nhs.uk/design-system/patterns">Hub page pattern</a>.</p>

  <h2 class="nhsuk-heading-l">When not to use a card</h2>
  <p>Do not use a card to replace or highlight content on the page.</p>
  <p>Before using a card consider these components first:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><a href="https://service-manual.nhs.uk/design-system/components/details">Details:</a> Makes a page easier to scan by letting users reveal more detailed information.</li>
    <li><a href="https://service-manual.nhs.uk/design-system/components/expander">Expander:</a> Make a complex topic easier to digest by letting users reveal more detailed information.</li>
    <li><a href="https://service-manual.nhs.uk/design-system/components/inset-text">Inset text:</a> Helps users identify and understand important content on the page.</li>
    <li><a href="https://service-manual.nhs.uk/design-system/components/tabs">Tabs:</a> Lets users navigate between related sections of content, displaying 1 section at a time.</li>
    <li><a href="https://service-manual.nhs.uk/design-system/components/warning-callout">Warning callout:</a> Helps users identify and understand warning content on a page.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 class="nhsuk-heading-l">How to use a card</h2>
  <p>Make a card easy to scan for relevant and actionable information.</p>
  <p>You can include multiple elements, such as a heading, text, image, and link. If you include a link, the link should mirror the heading of the page it links to.</p>
  <p>A card can be either clickable or non-clickable, for example, a clickable card will have a single link or action and the hit area will wrap the entire card. A non-clickable card can include multiple links.</p>
  <p>For a clickable card, avoid wrapping the entire card in an anchor tag as this can be a difficult experience for screen reader users.</p>
  <p>There are 4 types of cards:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Primary card</li>
    <li>Primary card (with chevron)</li>
    <li>Secondary card</li>
    <li>Image card</li>
  </ul>

  <h3 class="nhsuk-heading-m">Primary card</h3>
  <p>Primary cards are small clickable cards that can include a heading by itself or a heading, text, and links.</p>
  <p>Use the primary card to signpost important content or actions, helping users reach popular services without navigating deeper.</p>

